==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Strake
<hw>Strake</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Streak</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A streak.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<au>Spenser.</au>⟦ldquo⟧White <xex>strake</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Gen. xxx.
37.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An iron band by which the fellies of a wheel are
secured to each other, being not continuous, as the tire is, but made up
of separate pieces.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld> <def>One breadth of planks or
plates forming a continuous range on the bottom or sides of a vessel,
reaching from the stem to the stern; a streak.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The planks or plates next the keel are called the
<xex>garboard strakes</xex>; the next, or the heavy strakes at the
bilge, are the <xex>bilge strakes</xex>; the next, from the water line
to the lower port sill, the <xex>wales</xex>; and the upper parts of the
sides, the <xex>sheer strakes</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A trough for washing broken ore,
gravel, or sand; a launder.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Strale</ent>⟦br⟧
